    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:7d5f46f7-e8bb-4829-9351-3ecc4ecf4616",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 32-year-old woman who arrives looking slightly disheveled but strikingly energetic, dressed in bright mismatched layers and several pieces of costume jewelry that suggest impulsive recent spending. Her speech is rapid and expressive, and she shifts quickly between laughing, irritation, and tearfulness. On some days she presents exhausted, slowed, and withdrawn, describing long stretches of low mood, hopelessness, and difficulty getting out of bed; on other days she reports periods of decreased need for sleep, racing thoughts, inflated confidence, and starting multiple ambitious projects that she struggles to complete. She often says she feels like her mind can be either \"too fast\" or \"too heavy.\"\n\n{patientName} works intermittently as a freelance graphic designer, a role that suits her creativity but has become difficult to sustain because of fluctuating concentration, missed deadlines, and inconsistent sleep. She lives with a close friend who has become an important support and sometimes helps monitor medication adherence and warning signs of mood escalation. She enjoys painting, late-night music playlists, yoga classes when she is stable, and spontaneous weekend trips, though these outings have occasionally become financially reckless during elevated mood states.\n\nIn her daily life, {patientName} has a variable routine. During depressive phases she isolates herself, skips meals, and neglects household tasks. During elevated periods she becomes highly social, calls friends at odd hours, makes expansive plans, and may engage in risky online shopping or impulsive relationship decisions. Alcohol use is occasional but tends to increase during periods of emotional instability; she denies illicit substance use. She has one young child and feels significant guilt about times when her symptoms have interfered with parenting consistency.\n\nHer family describes her as deeply intelligent, imaginative, and warm, but also someone whose emotional intensity has caused recurrent strain in relationships. She has a history of partial insight: when stable, she recognizes prior episodes as illness-related, but during elevated states she may minimize symptoms and resist treatment. She presents as a realistic patient with chronic mood instability, psychosocial stress, and periods of functional impairment that are characteristic of bipolar spectrum illness."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:2bafca4a-f855-49b2-9faa-7971dfd7809a",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a several-year history of episodic mood disturbance beginning in her early 20s, with prior outpatient psychiatric treatment for depression before a later recognition of bipolar spectrum symptoms. She has had one previous psychiatric hospitalization at age 27 after several days of near-total insomnia, escalating agitation, and impulsive behavior. Past medical history is otherwise notable for obesity and migraine headaches. She had an appendectomy in adolescence and a cesarean section in her late 20s.\n\nShe reports irregular adherence to mood-stabilizing medication in the past, often stopping treatment when she begins to feel \"normal\" or when she dislikes sedation and weight gain. She sleeps poorly during mood elevation and may go 3 to 4 hours per night without feeling tired. During depressive periods she can sleep excessively, miss work, and withdraw from friends. She denies current pregnancy. There is no known seizure disorder. She occasionally drinks wine on weekends and has been counseled to avoid alcohol excess because of mood destabilization and medication interactions.\n\nPsychosocially, {patientName} has experienced recurrent occupational instability, periods of debt related to impulsive spending, and interpersonal conflict during episodes of irritability or emotional lability. She remains engaged in outpatient psychiatry intermittently and is open to treatment, especially when symptoms and their impact on parenting are discussed concretely."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}